external.description:
"Death shall come on swift wings to him that touches the tomb of the Pharaoh." ⚰️🐍

It is the most famous warning in history. When Howard Carter cracked open the seal of King Tutankhamun’s tomb in 1922, he revealed the greatest treasure the world had ever seen. But did he also unleash an ancient evil?

Within months, the expedition's financier, Lord Carnarvon, was dead. The lights in Cairo mysteriously went out. A canary was eaten by a cobra. The world was convinced: The Mummy’s Curse was real.

But what if the "Curse of the Pharaohs" wasn't created by an ancient priest, but by a jealous journalist?

In this episode, we open the files on the 1922 excavation to separate the gold from the lies. We explore Howard Carter’s diaries and the real cause of Lord Carnarvon’s death (spoiler: it involves a razor and a mosquito, not a ghost). We reveal how a media war between the London Times and rival reporters like Arthur Weigall invented the curse to sell papers.

We also dive into the strange involvement of Sherlock Holmes creator Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, who used his influence to turn a medical tragedy into a supernatural sensation, and debunk the separate folklore of the British Museum’s "Unlucky Mummy."

We’re digging up the truth on:
The Post Hoc Fallacy: Why bad timing isn't the same as a curse.
The Media Hoax: How "Fake News" was born in the Valley of the Kings.
The Science: How an infected insect bite became a global legend.

external.description:
Would you swap your body to save your life? Even if it meant losing your mind? 🧠✂️

It sounds like the plot of a horror movie or a Mary Shelley novel, but for Dr. Sergio Canavero, the world’s first human Head Transplant isn't fiction—it’s the next step in human evolution.

In this episode, we dissect the unsettling science behind the HEAVEN and GEMINI procedures, the audacious plan to sever a human head and fuse it onto a donor body using "biological glue" (Polyethylene Glycol). We dive deep into the story of Valery Spiridonov, the Russian computer scientist who volunteered to be the first test subject, only to back out for a very human reason: love.

But is this medical genius, or just "rotten science"?

We explore the terrifying hurdles that Canavero ignores: the impossible task of reconnecting a spinal cord, the nightmare of immune rejection, and the psychological horror of waking up in a stranger's skin. We also look back at the gruesome history of Robert J. White’s monkey head transplants to see why the medical community is screaming "STOP."

We’re cutting into the controversy:
The Procedure: How do you keep a severed head alive?
The Ethics: If we can do it, should we?
The Reality: Why experts say the result would be a fate worse than death.

Prepare yourself. This is the story of the ultimate identity crisis.

🎧 Press PLAY to enter the operating room of the impossible.

📌 AI Won’t Kill Cybersecurity Jobs, Here’s Why: An Analysis of Increasing Vulnerabilities https://www.cyberhub.blog/article/15807-ai-wont-kill-cybersecurity-jobs-heres-why-an-analysis-of-increasing-vulnerabilities

external.description:
The integration of AI in software development is often perceived as a threat to cybersecurity jobs. However, a closer examination reveals that AI is more likely to create additional security challenges rather than eliminate jobs. AI-generated applications, developed rapidly and often without a deep understanding of secure coding practices, are prone to vulnerabilities. This trend is exacerbated by large enterprises prioritizing speed to market over robust security measures, leading to an increase in cybersecurity issues.

Technically, AI-generated code may lack the rigor of human-developed code, especially in areas requiring nuanced understanding of security principles. This can result in applications that are more susceptible to attacks, thereby increasing the workload for cybersecurity professionals who must identify and mitigate these vulnerabilities.

The implications for the cybersecurity landscape are profound. As AI becomes more prevalent in software development, the volume of vulnerabilities is expected to rise. This surge in security issues will necessitate a larger workforce of cybersecurity experts to address these challenges, potentially leading to job growth in the field.

From an expert perspective, while AI can assist in automating certain aspects of cybersecurity, the complexity and context-specific nature of many security issues require human intervention. AI tools may help in detecting vulnerabilities, but human expertise is essential for understanding the broader context and implementing effective solutions.

In conclusion, rather than reducing the need for cybersecurity professionals, AI is likely to increase demand for their skills. The rapid development and deployment of AI-generated applications will introduce more vulnerabilities, creating more work for cybersecurity experts. This dynamic underscores the continuing importance of human expertise in maintaining robust cybersecurity defenses.
external.title: AI Won’t Kill Cybersecurity Jobs, Here’s Why: An Analysis of Increasing Vulnerabilities

From a cybersecurity perspective, this ruling highlights the importance of data security in large, consolidated tech companies. With Meta now controlling multiple major platforms, the volume of user data under its management is substantial. This centralization of data increases the potential impact of security breaches, as a single incident could compromise information across multiple services. Cybersecurity professionals should be aware of this increased risk and the need for robust security measures to protect centralized user data. The consolidation of platforms under Meta's control means that security breaches could have far-reaching consequences, affecting users across multiple services. This underscores the importance of comprehensive security strategies that address the unique challenges posed by large-scale data consolidation. Cybersecurity experts must consider the implications of such rulings on data management and protection practices within the tech industry. The ruling also serves as a reminder of the ongoing need for vigilant cybersecurity practices in the face of industry consolidation. As companies like Meta continue to expand their control over multiple platforms, the importance of comprehensive data protection strategies becomes even more critical. Cybersecurity professionals should monitor these developments closely and ensure that security practices are adequate to address the risks associated with such consolidations. In conclusion, while the ruling is a legal win for Meta, it emphasizes the critical need for enhanced cybersecurity measures to protect the vast amounts of user data now under its control.

From review of Yossi Yovel’s The Genius Bat.

Bats aren’t blind — and they can drink your blood without you noticing
(£) www.thetimes.com/culture/book...

images.alt:
Text:

His book, The Genius Bat, is at its best in these moments, when it asks us to widen our perception and consider, bat-like, how we also sense through sound: how our own voices come differently to us because we hear their vibrations, in part, through our skulls; or how we excel in pinpointing the direction of a sound because of the large gap between our ears. To think like this is to make bats seem less alien (or us more so).

There is an interesting section on reciprocal altruism in vampire bats. Vampires must drink 15ml of blood a night — half their body weight, about half a serving of whisky. They get it from living animals — cows, pigs, horses, birds and occasionally humans — and are so gentle that they can drink for half an hour without waking up their victim. Missing a couple of nights can be fatal, and so bats share with those who fail to get a meal. Relationships between friendly bats in the same roost can be more important than family ties when it comes to who they share with. They remember who has previously shared food with them, even over long periods of time, gradually building a mutual trust. It is one of the best documented examples of sharing in non-human animals.
